{"section": "A.8", "question": "If squad A is on the ground floor and shares a common hexside with squad B, which is on the first floor of the building, are the squads considered ADJACENT?", "expected_answer": "No, because to be ADJACENT, squad A would need to be able to advanced in APh into the location of Squad B, which isn't possible.", "assistant_response": "The squads are not considered adjacent if one is on the ground floor and the other is on the first floor, even if they share a common hexside. This is because adjacency in Advanced Squad Leader typically requires both squads to be on the same level of elevation. The rules specify that units on different levels within the same hex cannot see or target each other with fire, which implies they are not considered adjacent for purposes like movement or combat engagements【4:16†source】.", "judgment": "partial", "comments": "It got the answer right, but the explanation was wrong."}
{"section": "A4.34", "question": "How do you determine LOS when Infantry are using Bypass movement?", "expected_answer": "The ATTACKER has the option to make its one allowed LOS check per attack to either hex vertex along a hexside traversed by a unit moving in Bypass (thus a choice of two vertices for one hexside Bypass, three vertices for two hexsides Bypassed, etc.)", "assistant_response": "To determine Line of Sight (LOS) when infantry are using Bypass movement in Advanced Squad Leader, you need to consider these specific rules:\n\n1. **Vertices Options**: A unit firing at an infantry unit using Bypass does not have to trace its LOS to the center of the target hex. Instead, the firing unit has the option to make its one allowed LOS check per attack to either hex vertex along a hexside traversed by the unit moving in Bypass. This creates multiple options for determining LOS: two vertices for one hexside Bypass, three vertices for two hexsides Bypassed, and so on【4:0†source】.\n\n2. **Open Ground Bypass**: If the LOS of the firing unit reaches an Open Ground Bypass hexside vertex unobstructed, that unit can claim a LOS and a First Fire -2 DRM for non-Assault Movement in the open【4:0†source】.\n\n3. **Obstacles**: A wall or hedge in the target hex is not considered an obstacle to LOS even if the target unit may be in Bypass on the other side of that hex. However, the wall or hedge's TEM applies if it is crossed by the LOS【4:0†source】.\n\nThis provides a tactical advantage to firing units against those using Bypass movement, as they can exploit the lack of cover typically involved in Bypass maneuvers.", "judgment": "correct", "comments": ""}
{"section": "A4.431", "question": "When can transfers of SW/Guns occur?", "expected_answer": "During the RPh, at the start of their APh, or as a result of the creation of a sub-unit from an MMC", "assistant_response": "Transfers of SW (Support Weapons) or Guns can occur under specific circumstances in Advanced Squad Leader. They can be transferred between different Good Order unpinned units in the same location during specific phases: the Rally Phase (RPh), at the start of their Advance Phase (APh), or as a result of creating a sub-unit from a Multi-Man Counter (MMC)【4:15†eASLRB_v2.07-postprocessed.pdf】. \n\nAdditionally, personnel units can drop or change possession freely at no movement factor cost during their Movement Phase (MPh), Advance Phase (APh), or the start of the Close Combat Phase (CCPh)【4:6†eASLRB_v2.07-postprocessed.pdf】. The transfer or recovery of a SW/Gun on a vehicle in motion can only be achieved by the passengers or riders of that vehicle【4:15†eASLRB_v2.07-postprocessed.pdf】.", "judgment": "correct", "comments": ""}
